    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nOnce entered an empty loop such as 'while 1:pass', Ctrl-C will have no effect even if the loop code is wrapped by a try-except-KeyboardInterrupt construct\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\r\ntry:\r\n\tprint('enter loop')\r\n\twhile 1:\r\n\t\tpass\r\nexcept KeyboardInterrupt:\r\n\tprint('ctrl-c')\r\n```\r\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nLoop should always breakable by a Ctrl-C\n\n### OS\n\nmacOS\n\n### Python version\n\n3.9.6\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.0.2\n\n### Additional context\n\nthis bug can be worked around by replacing 'pass' with 'print(\"\", end=\"\")' or other NOP equivalent code",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I don't think Cython checks for keyboard interrupts at all. I think they only get detected when control returns to the Python interpreter.\r\n\r\nThat obviously isn't ideal in that it makes some types of Cython code impossible to interrupt, but I suspect we don't want to change this.",
